bug.short_desc: the data written by liveusb-creator is not recognizable to virt-manager or Nautilus

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 1149370 screenshot
Description of problem: I follow the default steps to write Workstation-iso onto my usb stick which has some data on it.Then I tried to use that usb stick to do some installation ,but found that the virt-manager can't recognize the workstation data,and complains that "No bootable devices". It seems that the Nautilus can't recognize also the data
Version-Release number of selected component (if applicable): liveusb-creator-3.92.1-1.fc24.noarch
How reproducible: always
Steps to Reproduce: 1.Insert usb stick 2.run liveusb-creator 3.choose Fedora Workstation option to do the writing
Actual results:
Expected results:
Additional info:
Was there any problem while writing the image to the drive? Did it take too long or short?

Created attachment 1149385 some maybe-useful information
As you can see,the fdisk can recognize the data well

(In reply to Martin Bříza from comment #2) > Was there any problem while writing the image to the drive? Did it take too > long or short?
It seems that there is no problem happened.I was trying to reproduce another bug on another machine,so I can't tell whether it has taken too long or too short. The only thing I can tell for sure is that I had seen the "finished" notice,before I tried to do the installation.
Now the Nautilus can recognize the data well after I reinsert the usb stick.
